  <div class="one-third column">
    <h4 class="myheadings">Zone B &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
      <table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10" width="100%">
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V375</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V475</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V500D</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V575</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V675</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V775</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V1075</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V2073</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V3073</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <br>
      <p>Zone B allows the surround back channels to be redirected to a second area such as an outdoor entertaining area.</p>
      <p>This means you can have 5.1 channels active in the lounge room with the same audio source being played through a pair of Yamaha outdoor speakers.</p>
      <p><img src="images/zoneb.jpg" width="100%" alt="Zone B"></p>
    </div>
    <h4 class="myheadings">Zone 2 / 3 &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
      <table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10" width="100%">
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V375</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V475</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V500D</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V575</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V675</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V775</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V1075</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V2073</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V3073</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <br>
      <p>Different to Zone B, Zone 2 (and Zone 3) allows different sources to be played in two areas of the home at the same time.</p>
      <p>Someone can be watching a movie in 5.2 channel surround sound in the lounge room while music stored on a PC or Mac is being streamed to another area of the home - all being powered by the one receiver.</p>
      <p>All Yamaha’s Zone 2/3 receivers support network functionality which means the AV Controller app can be used for simple wireless control of the audio in each zone via a smartphone or tablet.</p>
      <p><em>*The RX-V3073 &amp; RX-V2073 support Zone 3</em></p>
      <p><img src="images/zone2-3.jpg" width="100%" alt="Zone 2"></p>
    </div>
    <h4 class="myheadings">HDMI Zone B &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
      <table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10" width="100%">
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V375</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V475</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V500D</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V575</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V675</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V775</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V1075</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V2073</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V3073</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <br>
      <p>With dual HDMI outputs, HDMI Zone B allows the same video to be viewed on two devices at the same time.</p>
      <p>The HDMI Zone B function allows you to still enjoy a multi-channel experience in the main area while audio and video is played back in the second area through the connected television.</p>
      <p><img src="images/hdmi-zoneb.jpg" width="100%" alt="HDMI Zone B"></p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="one-third column">
    <h4 class="myheadings">HDMI Zone 2 &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
      <table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10" width="100%">
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V375</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V475</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V500D</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V575</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V675</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V775</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V1075</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V2073</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V3073</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <br>
      <p>This feature allows two Full HD video sources to be sent to different areas of the home simultaneously.</p>
      <p>Watch a Blu-ray movie in the main zone while someone watches Foxtel outside on the TV mounted under the patio. HDMI Zone 2 also means you can use the internal amplifiers to run audio out to that second zone, resulting in not only Full HD picture but great quality sound as well.</p>
      <p><img src="images/hdmi-zone2.jpg" width="100%" ></p>
    </div>
    <h4 class="myheadings">HDMI Zone 4 &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
      <table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="10" width="100%">
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V375</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V475</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V500D</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V575</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V675</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V775</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V1075</td>
          <td class="incompatible">RX-V2073</td>
          <td class="compatible">RX-V3073</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <br>
      <p>Similar to HDMI Zone 2, this feature allows Full HD content to be played in another area of the home.</p>
      <p>The difference is that audio and video is sent via HDMI so you can’t use the internal amplifiers of the receiver to send audio to Zone 4.</p>
      <p>For example, in a 4 zone configuration the user may be watching a Blu-ray movie in 5.2 channel surround sound in the main zone, while radio is playing in Zone 2, Pandora® Internet radio service in Zone 3, and Foxtel playing on the television in Zone 4.</p>
      <p><img src="images/hdmi-zone4.jpg" width="100%" ></p>
    </div>
    <h4 class="myheadings">Available Sources for Multi-zone &gt;&gt;</h4>
    <div class="thecontent">
